To run a Locust test suite on a cluster of AWS instances, you can follow these general steps:

Set up the AWS instances: Launch the required number of EC2 instances and configure them to use a common security group and IAM role.
(PS- Alternatively you can create the cluster using Terraform and Ansible)

Install Locust: Install Locust on each instance by following the installation instructions provided on the Locust website.

Write your Locust test script: Develop your test script and ensure that it's ready for running on multiple instances.

Configure Locust: Configure Locust to run the test on multiple instances by setting
the --master flag on the master node and --worker flag on the worker nodes.

Start the master node: Start the master node by running the Locust command with the appropriate parameters,
including the IP addresses of the worker nodes.

Start the worker nodes: Start the worker nodes by running the Locust command with the appropriate parameters,
including the IP address of the master node.

Monitor the test: Use the Locust web interface to monitor the test,
including the number of users, response time, and other performance metrics.

Analyze the results: Once the test is complete, analyze the results to identify any performance issues and optimize your application accordingly.

It's worth noting that there are also various tools and services available that can simplify the process of running Locust tests on AWS,
such as the Locust AWS module and the Locust Cloud service.
These tools can help you to automate the setup and configuration of your Locust test environment,
as well as provide additional features for scaling and monitoring your tests.